observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

a. Instruct the OIC-Municipal Engineer, with the assistance of the MPDC, to:

Provide status report on the implementation of afore-mentioned PPAs, including the reasons for non-implementation;

Develop a clear implementation plan with a defined timeframe and regularly prepare monitoring reports to track the progress; and

Supervise the implementation of PPAs and conduct regular inspections to ensure timely completion;

b. Require the Municipal Assessor to closely monitor the reply of the Office of the Provincial Assessor and, if necessary, write a follow-up letter to expedite the assessment needed for the purchase of two lots; 

c. Instruct the Local Development Council to meticulously plan and evaluate the feasibility of each PPA included in the AIP to ensure that these PPAs are procurement-and-implementation ready for efficient execution; and

d. Require the MPDC, with the assistance of the BAC, to prioritize the procurement of the three unimplemented PPAs and ensure that the target implementation set forth in the AIP is executed on time to deliver the intended benefits to the constituents in support to the constitutional objective of promoting the general welfare and improving the quality of life for all.

We recommended that Management:

a. Direct the BAC to conduct a pre-procurement conference for procurement of infrastructure and goods with approved budget for the contract of above ₱5,000,000.00 and ₱2,000,000.00, respectively;

b. Require the BAC Secretariat to issue a notice letter to all bidders who have submitted their bid proposal in the succeeding procurement activities;

c. Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to invite at least one representative from a duly recognized private group in a sector or discipline relevant to the procurement and ensure that the private group to which the observer belongs to is properly indicated;

d. Instruct the TWG to indicate in the Post-Qualification Evaluation Report the actions taken in the verification with concerned regulatory bodies and the validation of competence, experience and availability of the bidder as well as the inspection and testing of capacities of the equipment to be used or leased for infrastructure projects and the result of verification and testing of the goods/product and the after-sales or maintenance capabilities in the case of procurement of goods; 

e. Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to ensure that a performance security is secured and posted before the contract signing;

f. Require the BAC Secretariat to strictly observe the prescribed period of posting the NOA and NTP in the PhilGEPs website;

g. Instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to immediately notify the bidder in writing in the event the bidder fails the criteria for post-qualification; and

h. Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to cause the refund of ₱152,465.85 representing discrepancy in figures and in words for the bid amount of the bidder for the project “Concreting of Road with Drainage System at Luna Street, Barangay Poblacion”; and

i. Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to strictly observe the allowed maximum period for all stages of procurement activities and ensure that contract signing is made first before the issuance of NTP.

a. Institute actions to strictly enforce the immediate settlement/liquidation of cash advances of accountable officials/employees who are still in the service;

b. Exhaust all possible means to collect the cash advances from previous employees who are no longer in the service, otherwise proceed against the signatories of the clearance, who are still in the service;

c. Request authority to write off from the Commission on Audit should the cash advances remain uncollected despite exhausted recovery efforts.

We recommended that Management instruct the:

a. GSO to conduct inventory semesterly and submit the report to the Audit Team with every July 31st and January 31st of each year; 

b. Municipal Accountant to use the Perpetual Inventory Method, wherein the supplies purchased shall be coursed through the appropriate inventory account and the corresponding expense account shall be debited upon issuance based on the SSMI.

a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to identify the affected accounts and make the necessary adjusting journals entries in the books of the agency;

b. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to immediately transfer the corresponding payable accounts from one fund to the other by availing the services of their authorized depository bank through debit and credit memo to ease the preparation of payment between intra-agency accounts;

c. Require the Municipal Accountant to record in the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds accounts subsequent intra-agency receivable and payable transactions; and

d. Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that recording of deposits and disbursements are made in the correct fund and to observe monthly reconciliation of book balances of each depository bank accounts.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Identify all the assets recorded in the books;


Ensure that all PPEs subject for depreciation have been provided with depreciation cost;

Make necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the balances of the affected accounts; and

Update and provide copy of updated SLs of all PPE accounts with the corresponding Accumulated Depreciation to the Audit Team.

We recommended that the LCE require:

The Municipal Accountant to impose liquidated damages amounting to ₱842,400.00 to the supplier for the late delivery of the medical bus;

The GSO to submit service warranty booklet for inspection;

The Municipal Engineer to submit the detailed breakdown/derivation of unit cost of items amounting ₱11,700,000.00;

The Inspection and Acceptance Committee to submit a written explanation as to the variation in the model of ECG, as per bid proposal FX-8100/FCP-8100 but the actual item delivered was Fukuda M-E Cardisuny C120; and

The Municipal Engineer to inspect and prepare a checklist on the portions of the medical bus which have been poorly done, and require the supplier to polish the work.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Assessor to facilitate the preparation of the updated Report on Real Property Assessment and copy thereof be furnished to the Municipal Treasurer for updating of the RPTAR;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the RPTAR which will be used as basis in the setting-up of RPT/SET Receivables to reflect the actual collectibles from RPT and SET in the financial statements;
Require the Municipal Accountant to take up in the books the delinquent accounts amounting to ₱1,968,789.40; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that correct accounting entries are recorded in the books of accounts to present a reliable financial statement.

